			StaticText 'We introduce a novel 3D generation method for versatile and high-quality 3D asset creation. The cornerstone is a unified Structured LATent (SLAT) representation which allows decoding to different output formats, such as Radiance Fields, 3D Gaussians, and meshes. This is achieved by integrating a sparsely-populated 3D grid with dense multiview visual features extracted from a powerful vision foundation model, comprehensively capturing both structural (geometry) and textural (appearance) information while maintaining flexibility during decoding. We employ rectified flow transformers tailored for SLAT as our 3D generation models and train models with up to 2 billion parameters on a large 3D asset dataset of 500K diverse objects. Our model generates high-quality results with text or image conditions, significantly surpassing existing methods, including recent ones at similar scales. We showcase flexible output format selection and local 3D editing capabilities which were not offered by previous models. Code, model, and data will be released.'

			StaticText 'We introduce a novel 3D generation method for versatile and high-quality 3D asset creation. The cornerstone is a unified Structured LATent (SLAT) representation which allows decoding to different output formats, such as Radiance Fields, 3D Gaussians, and meshes. This is achieved by integrating a sparsely-populated 3D grid with dense multiview visual features extracted from a powerful vision foundation model, comprehensively capturing both structural (geometry) and textural (appearance) information while maintaining flexibility during decoding. We employ rectified flow transformers tailored for SLAT as our 3D generation models and train models with up to 2 billion parameters on a large 3D asset dataset of 500K diverse objects. Our model generates high-quality results with text or image conditions, significantly surpassing existing methods, including recent ones at similar scales. We showcase flexible output format selection and local 3D editing capabilities which were not offered by previous models. Code, model, and data will be released.'

		[185] blockquote '', visible
			StaticText 'We introduce a novel 3D generation method for versatile and high-quality 3D asset creation. The cornerstone is a unified Structured LATent (SLAT) representation which allows decoding to different output formats, such as Radiance Fields, 3D Gaussians, and meshes. This is achieved by integrating a sparsely-populated 3D grid with dense multiview visual features extracted from a powerful vision foundation model, comprehensively capturing both structural (geometry) and textural (appearance) information while maintaining flexibility during decoding. We employ rectified flow transformers tailored for SLAT as our 3D generation models and train models with up to 2 billion parameters on a large 3D asset dataset of 500K diverse objects. Our model generates high-quality results with text or image conditions, significantly surpassing existing methods, including recent ones at similar scales. We showcase flexible output format selection and local 3D editing capabilities which were not offered by previous models. Code, model, and data will be released.'

		[380] heading 'Abstract'
		[382] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'We introduce a novel 3D generation method for versatile and high-quality 3D asset creation. The cornerstone is a unified Structured LATent ('
			StaticText 'SLat'
			StaticText ') representation which allows decoding to different output formats, such as Radiance Fields, 3D Gaussians, and meshes. This is achieved by integrating a sparsely-populated 3D grid with dense multiview visual features extracted from a powerful vision foundation model, comprehensively capturing both structural (geometry) and textural (appearance) information while maintaining flexibility during decoding.'
		[385] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'We employ rectified flow transformers tailored for'
			StaticText 'SLat'
			StaticText 'as our 3D generation models and train models with up to 2 billion parameters on a large 3D asset dataset of 500K diverse objects. Our model generates high-quality results with text or image conditions, significantly surpassing existing methods, including recent ones at similar scales. We showcase flexible output format selection and local 3D editing capabilities which were not offered by previous models. Code, model, and data are available on our'
			[387] link 'project page', clickable, url='https://trellis3d.github.io/'
			StaticText '.'
		StaticText '{strip}'
		[391] image '[Uncaptioned image]', url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1/x1.png'
		[392] figure ''
			[393] Figcaption ''
				StaticText 'Figure 1'
				StaticText ':'
				StaticText 'High-quality 3D assets generated by our method in various formats from text or image prompts (using GPT-4o and DALL-E 3). Our method enables versatile generation in about 10 seconds, offering vivid appearances with 3D Gaussians or Radiance Fields and detailed geometries with meshes. It also supports flexible 3D editing.'
				[397] emphasis ''
					StaticText 'Best viewed with zoom-in.'
		[400] heading '1 Introduction'
			StaticText '1'
		[404] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'While AI Generated Content (AIGC) for 3D has made tremendous progress in recent years'
			StaticText '['
			[406] link '68', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib68'
				StaticText '68'
			StaticText ','
			[408] link '48', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib48'
				StaticText '48'
			StaticText ','
			[410] link '87', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib87'
				StaticText '87'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText ', existing 3D generative models still fall short in generation quality compared to their 2D predecessors, where large image generation models'
			StaticText '['
			[413] link '19', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib19'
				StaticText '19'
			StaticText ','
			[415] link '9', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib9'
				StaticText '9'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText 'have enabled ready-to-use tools that exert a profound impact on today‚Äôs digital industry.'
		[419] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'Unlike 2D images, typically represented by pixel grids, 3D data encompasses diverse representations like meshes, point clouds, Radiance Fields'
			StaticText '['
			[421] link '59', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib59'
				StaticText '59'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText ', and 3D Gaussians'
			StaticText '['
			[424] link '33', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib33'
				StaticText '33'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText '. Each format is tailored for specific applications and may encounter difficulties when adapted for other tasks. For instance, while numerous studies'
			StaticText '['
			[427] link '12', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib12'
				StaticText '12'
			StaticText ','
			[429] link '25', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib25'
				StaticText '25'
			StaticText ','
			[431] link '41', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib41'
				StaticText '41'
			StaticText ','
			[433] link '72', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib72'
				StaticText '72'
			StaticText ','
			[435] link '96', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib96'
				StaticText '96'
			StaticText ','
			[437] link '102', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib102'
				StaticText '102'
			StaticText ','
			[439] link '106', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib106'
				StaticText '106'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText 'have utilized 3D representations like meshes or implicit fields'
			StaticText '['
			[442] link '58', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib58'
				StaticText '58'
			StaticText ','
			[444] link '66', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib66'
				StaticText '66'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText 'for object geometry generation, they often falter in detailed appearance modeling compared to those relying on representations equipped with advanced volumetric rendering capabilities ('
			[446] emphasis ''
				StaticText 'e.g'
			StaticText '.'
			StaticText ', 3D Gaussians and Radiance Fields). Conversely, generative models based on Radiance Fields or 3D Gaussians'
			StaticText '['
			[449] link '91', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib91'
				StaticText '91'
			StaticText ','
			[451] link '37', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib37'
				StaticText '37'
			StaticText ','
			[453] link '104', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib104'
				StaticText '104'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText 'excel in rendering high-quality appearances but strruggle with plausible geometry extraction. Moreover, the unique structured or unstructured characteristics of different representations complicate processing through a consistent network architecture. These issues hinder the development of a standardized 3D generative modeling paradigm, in contrast to the consensus in recent advanced 2D generation methods that learn generative models within a unified latent space'
			StaticText '['
			[456] link '73', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib73'
				StaticText '73'
			StaticText ','
			[458] link '19', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib19'
				StaticText '19'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText '.'
		[462] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'In this paper, we aim to develop a'
			[463] emphasis ''
				StaticText 'unified and versatile latent space'
			StaticText 'that facilitates high-quality 3D generation across various representations, accommodating diverse downstream requirements. This problem is highly challenging and has rarely been addressed by previous approaches. To tackle this, our primary strategy is to introduce explicit sparse 3D structures in the latent space design. These structures enable decoding into different 3D representations by characterizing attributes within the local voxels surrounding an object, as is evidenced by recent advancements in the 3D reconstruction field'
			StaticText '['
			[465] link '54', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib54'
				StaticText '54'
			StaticText ','
			[467] link '74', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib74'
				StaticText '74'
			StaticText ','
			[469] link '22', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib22'
				StaticText '22'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText '. This approach also allows for efficient high-resolution modeling by bypassing voxels without 3D information'
			StaticText '['
			[472] link '45', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib45'
				StaticText '45'
			StaticText ','
			[474] link '72', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib72'
				StaticText '72'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText ', and introduces locality that facilitates flexible editing.'
		[478] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'However, even with such structures, achieving high-quality decoding into different 3D representations is still non-trivial, as it requires the latent representation to encapsulate both comprehensive geometry and appearance information of the 3D assets. To address this issue, our second strategy is to equip the sparse structures with a powerful vision foundation model'
			StaticText '['
			[480] link '65', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib65'
				StaticText '65'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText 'for detailed information encoding, given its demonstrated strong 3D awareness'
			StaticText '['
			[483] link '18', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib18'
				StaticText '18'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText 'and capability for detailed representation'
			StaticText '['
			[486] link '112', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib112'
				StaticText '112'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText '. This approach bypasses the need for a dedicated 3D encoder, and eliminates the costly pre-fitting process of aligning 3D data with specific representations'
			StaticText '['
			[489] link '91', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib91'
				StaticText '91'
			StaticText ','
			[491] link '104', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib104'
				StaticText '104'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText '.'
		[495] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'Given these two strategies, we introduce Structured LATents ('
			StaticText 'SLat'
			StaticText '), a unified 3D latent representation for high-quality, versatile 3D generation.'
			StaticText 'SLat'
			StaticText'marries'
			[498] emphasis ''
				StaticText'sparse structures'
			StaticText 'with powerful'
			[499] emphasis ''
				StaticText 'visual representations'
			StaticText '. It defines local latents on active voxels intersecting the object‚Äôs surface. The local latents are encoded by fusing and processing image features from densely rendered views of the 3D asset, while attaches them onto active voxels. These features, derived from powerful pretrained vision encoders'
			StaticText '['
			[501] link '65', clickable, url='https://arxiv.org/html/2412.01506v1#bib.bib65'
				StaticText '65'
			StaticText ']'
			StaticText ', capture detailed geometric and visual characteristics, complementing the coarse structure provided by the active voxels. Different decoders can then be applied to map'
			StaticText 'SLat'
			StaticText 'to diverse 3D representations of high quality.'
		[506] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'Building on'
			StaticText 'SLat'
			StaticText ', we train a family of large 3D generation models, dubbed'
			[508] emphasis ''
				StaticText 'Trellis'
			StaticText 'in this paper, with text prompts or images as conditions. A two stage pipeline is applied which first generates the sparse structure of'
			StaticText 'SLat'
			StaticText ', followed by generating the latent vectors for non-empty cells. We employ rectified flow transformers as our backbone models and adapt them properly to handle the sparsity in'
			StaticText 'SLat'
			StaticText '. We train'
			StaticText 'Trellis'
			StaticText 'with up to 2 billion parameters on a large dataset of carefully-collected 3D assets. Through extensive experiments, we show that our model can create high-quality 3D assets with detailed geometry and vivid texture, significantly surpassing previous methods. Moreover, it can easily generate 3D assets with different output formats to meet diverse downstream requirements.'
		[514] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'We summarize the notable features of our method below:'
		[516] list ''
			[517] listitem ''
				StaticText '‚Ä¢'
				[520] paragraph ''
					StaticText 'High quality.'
					StaticText 'It produces diverse 3D assets at high-quality with intricate shape and texture details.'
			[523] listitem ''
				StaticText '‚Ä¢'
				[526] paragraph ''
					StaticText 'Versatile generation.'
					StaticText 'It takes text or image prompts and can generate various final 3D representations including but not limited to Radiance Fields, 3D Gaussians, and meshes.'
			[529] listitem ''
				StaticText '‚Ä¢'
				[532] paragraph ''
					StaticText 'Flexible editing.'
					StaticText 'It enables flexible tuning-free 3D editing such as the deletion, addition, and replacement of local regions, guided by text or image prompts.'
			[535] listitem ''
				StaticText '‚Ä¢'
				[538] paragraph ''
					StaticText 'Fitting-free training.'
					StaticText 'No 3D fitting is needed for the training objects in the entire process.'
		[541] paragraph ''
			StaticText 'Given these strong performance and multifold advantages, we believe our new models can serve as powerful 3D generation foundations and unlock new possibilities for the 3D vision community. We hope our work can shed some light on 3D-representation-agnostic asset modeling, in contrast to the field‚Äôs relentless pursuit of and adaptation to new representations.'
			[542] emphasis ''
				StaticText 'All our code, model, and data are released to facilitate reproduction and downstream applications'
			StaticText '.'

I see various entries that match the search term "Machine Learning," including papers, books, and links to authors' profiles. Since the search results are not focused on "quantum computing," I believe that modifying the search query would offer better results. One way to modify the query could be changing the search term from "Machine Learning" to "quantum computing."

By observing the current accessibility tree, I notice that I can modify the search term by interacting with the element with ID [220], which is a textbox with a value of 'Machine Learning'. The 'Search' button is clickable and visible with an ID [228]. I can type the new search term 'quantum computing' into the textbox and then click the 'Search' button.

Let's think step-by-step. We are now on the arXiv.org website which is an open-access archive for scholarly articles in various fields, including physics, mathematics, and computer science. Our objective is to find a research paper on quantum computing. We can see that there is a search box with ID '50' and a combobox 'Field to search' with value 'All fields'. 

We can start by typing our search query into the search box. Since we are looking for a research paper on quantum computing, we can type 'quantum computing' into the search box. We will also press the Enter key after typing to submit our search query.

Let's think step-by-step. In the previous actions, we clicked on the 'Physics' link and opened a new tab with the URL 'https://arxiv.org'. The current webpage is https://arxiv.org/ which is a research paper repository. We want to find a research paper on quantum computing. We are currently on the homepage of arXiv and we see various links related to physics, including 'Astrophysics', 'Condensed Matter', and 'General Relativity and Quantum Cosmology'. We need to find the section that is most relevant to quantum computing.

In the links under 'Physics', we see a link 'Condensed Matter' which might be related to quantum computing. Let's explore this option.

However, 'Condensed Matter' has several sub-links, including 'Condensed Matter Disordered Systems and Neural Networks', 'Condensed Matter Materials Science', 'Condensed Matter Mesoscale and Nanoscale Physics', etc. There isn't an explicit link to 'Quantum Computing' but some of these sub-links might be relevant.

In the current state, it seems that none of the links directly corresponds to quantum computing. Since arXiv also has a search feature, a more direct approach would be to use the search bar to find relevant papers.

The search bar has the id [50]. The default field to search is 'All fields'. Our objective is to find a research paper on quantum computing.

		[177] blockquote '', visible
			StaticText 'The investigation of strongly-correlated quantum matter is challenging due to the curse of dimensionality and complex entanglement structures. This complexity is especially pronounced in the vicinity of continuous quantum phase transitions, where quantum fluctuations occur on all length scales. While quantum simulators give well-controlled access to strongly-correlated systems, the study of critical systems has been hampered by strong finite-size effects caused by diverging correlation lengths, and there has been limited progress on methods to probe many-body entanglement due to restrictions in measurement protocols. We address these challenges by using the multiscale entanglement renormalization ansatz (MERA) and implementing a holographic subsystem tomography on a fully-connected trapped-ion quantum computer. Our method accurately represents infinite systems and long-range correlations with few qubits, enabling the efficient extraction of observables and entanglement properties also at criticality. We observe a quantum phase transitions with spontaneous symmetry breaking and reveal the evolution of entanglement measures across the critical point. For the first time, we demonstrate log-law scaling of subsystem entanglement entropies at criticality on a digital quantum computer. This demonstrates the potential of MERA for a practicable investigation of strongly-correlated many-body systems on quantum computers.'

Let's think step-by-step. On the current webpage, we are already focused on "data science" skills and are trying to find a professional certificate that teaches Data Science. 

Our goal now is to find the certificates related to Data Science. Since the element we are interested in searching for is "Data Science," we should click on that option if available in the skills option. Therefore, our next action is searching for the "Data Science" checkbox and clicking on it.

Unfortunately, in the given accessibility tree, the "Data Science" checkbox is not visible. In order to proceed, we should scroll down the page.

In absence of specific date selection options, let's try the most likely generic navigation that could allow date selection - the link to the index page: 'Stays'. However if 'Stays' loads an entirely new page we could potentially link away and we will not have an obvious choice to choose the date if so proceed carefully.
